Web Enumeration ‚§µÔ∏è

I checked port 7443 and 7070 but the response was this ‚è¨

Openfire redirect page

So Now I checked port 5222 which indicated jabber was running but this port is actually for xmpp-client service running.

  • An¬†XMPP client¬†is any software or application that enables you to connect to an XMPP for instant messaging with other people over the Internet. There are many free clients you can use to do this, for many different devices and operating systems.

These are the free clients ,Reference: https://jabber.at/clients/

I will be using Gajim and pidgin both Tools on the way ‚è¨

Lets use Pidgin Tool first ‚è¨

Install this tool like this üîª

1

sudo apt install pidgin
  • Register a user with any Username, Email, Password but the server address should be the machine address that is 10.10.11.4 and the domain name will be jab.htb .

  • There is a plugin called Service Discovery , Enable it then use it to discover what services are involved with which subdomains along with its chats.

Enabling Service Discovery Plugin

  • Now the plugin is up so lets look for services from this server and I found these many , into a subdomain service called conference.jab.htb I got 2 chats ‚è¨

Accessing Chats

  • Now lets look for User Information from here ‚è¨

User Enumeration

  • I have to enter the Service Discovery name that I identified above that indicates the Search for user info that is search.jab.htb.

Specifying the subdomain name

  • Here I can filter out the output or we can access all the data by giving asterisk (*) as an input like this ‚è¨

Sorting the output

  • As a result I got these 2000+ many output as usernames ‚è¨

Users Informations

There is another Tool called Gajim that can be installed by this command in Debian machines ‚è¨

1

sudo apt install gajim

Now Lets run this Tool ‚è¨

  • Firstly I will be signing up with server name as jab.htb and with enabled Sign up Anonymously option.

Sign Up process

  • There is a warning page with will pop up like this , ignore that ‚è¨

Certificate verification popup

  • I got this successful page ‚è¨

  • Now lets set the hostname for enabling the server connection ‚è¨

Turn the Hostname option On and specify its address

  • Specify the Address of the server in this case the machine IP and the Type will be plain that will not be encrypted .

Connection establishing

  • As the Account setup so lets look into the Discover Services option with similar fashion like I did in Pidgin Tool.

Discover Services option

  • Enumerate the User Search Discovery further more ‚è¨

User Info Search discovery

  • Lets sort the output now ‚è¨

Sorting the output

  • As a result I got the usernames ‚è¨

Users Informations

But in all these Tools the problem was to copy all these Users Information at once , that was not possible so I recon further related to it and I got one hint that I could capture the Informations in packets with tcpdump Tool and then sort them like this ‚è¨

1
2

‚îå‚îÄ‚îÄ(kali„âøkali)-[~/Downloads/HTB/Jab]
‚îî‚îÄ$ sudo tcpdump -i tun0 -w users.pcap

I started the tcpdump Tool to capture the data on this tun0 interface and then searched all the users information again and then I stopped the capture.

Its time to sort the output that is captured in this users.pcap file , I will be using ‚è¨

  • grep - Shorting the output.
  • -a - This options specify to filter out the text content only
  • -E - Interpret PATTERN as extended regular expressions
  • '@' - Sorting Pattern string.
  • strings - This will print out the text part in a binary file.
1

cat users.pcap | grep -aE '@' | strings

Users Info sorted

Lets filter out the usernames only ‚è¨

1
2

‚îå‚îÄ‚îÄ(kali„âøkali)-[~/Downloads/HTB/Jab]
‚îî‚îÄ$ cat users.pcap |grep -aE '@' | strings | grep '<field var="Username"><value>' | sed "s/<\/item><item>/<\/item>\n<item>/g" | grep 'Username' | cut -d '>' -f 8 | cut -d '<' -f 1 | sed "s/ //g" > usernames.txt

As a result I got these username ‚è¨
